05735nam a22007455i 9781501760204DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017602047 a10.1515/97815017602042doi  a(DE-B1597)576588  a(OCoLC)1235904499  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0320002bisacsh1 aCronin, Glenn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDisenchanted Wanderer :bThe Apocalyptic Vision of Konstantin Leontiev /cGlenn Cronin. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b10 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNIU Series in Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tEnglish Names of Newspapers and Journals -- tNote on Translation, Transliteration, and Dates -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: “Beauty Is Truth, Truth Beauty” -- t1. The Divided Self -- t2. The Best of All Possible Worlds -- t3. The Gathering Storm -- t4. Desperate Times -- tPart Two: A Prophet in His Own Country -- t5. Russians, Greeks, and Slavs -- t6. The Social Organism -- t7. Blood Is Not Enough -- t8. The Tide of History -- tPart Three: Toward the Abyss -- t9. The Beginning of Wisdom -- t10. The Grand Inquisitor -- t11. Reactionary or Revolutionary? -- t12. The Feudalism of the Future -- t13. The Red Czar -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDisenchanted Wanderer is the first comprehensive English language study in over half a century of the life and ideas of Konstantin Nikolaevich Leontiev (1831–1891), one of the most important thinkers in nineteenth-century Russia on political, social, and religious matters. This work by Glenn Cronin gives the reader a broad overview of Leontiev's life and varied career as novelist, army doctor, diplomat, journalist, censor, and, late in life, ordained monk. Reviewing Leontiev's creative work and his writing on aesthetics and literary criticism—such figures as Belinsky, Turgenev, Gogol, Dostoevsky, and Tolstoy appear—Cronin goes on to examine Leontiev's socio-political writing and his theory of the rise and fall of cultures and civilizations, placing his thought in the context of his contemporaries and forbears including Hegel, Herzen and Nietzsche, as well as Danilevsky, Pobedonostsev and other major figures in Slavophile and Russian nationalist circles. Cronin also examines Leontiev's religious views, his ascetic brand of Orthodoxy informed by his experiences of the monastic communities of Mount Athos and OptinaPustyn, and his late attraction to Roman Catholicism under the influence of the theologian Vladimir Solovyev. Disenchanted Wanderer concludes with a review of Leontiev's prophetic vision for the twentieth century and his conviction that after a period of wars socialism would triumph under the banner of a new Constantine the Great. Cronin considers how far this vision foretold the rise to power of Joseph Stalin, an aspect of Leontiev's legacy which previously had not received the attention it merits. Elevating Leontiev to his proper place in the Russian literary pantheon, Cronin demonstrates that the man was not, as is often maintained, an amoralist and a political reactionary but rather a deeply moral thinker and a radical conservative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aRussian Byzantinism, Russian Conservatism,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE C